SIMPLE: intercalate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intercalate
<hw>In*ter"ca*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intercalated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Intercalating</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>intercalatus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>intercalare</ets> to intercalate to intercalate; <ets>inter</ets>
between + <ets>calare</ets> to call, proclaim. See
<er>Calendar</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chron.)</fld> <def>To insert, as a day or other
portion of time, in a calendar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To insert among others, as a verse in a stanza;
specif. <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, to introduce as a bed or stratum, between
the layers of a regular series of rocks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beds of fresh-water shells . . . are <qex>intercalated</qex> and
interstratified with the shale.</q> <rj><qau>Mantell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercalation</ent>⟦br⟧
